#X obj 136 515 envgen~ -curve 1 -suspoint 2 50 1 50 0.5 200 0, f 28;
#X text 43 361 Now with an exponential curve and a signal "gate" input to control the sustain stage. Note that in this case you can also retrigger with an impulse in the right inlet when sustaining., f 49;
#X text 422 19 The [adsr~] object from ELSE is dedicated to ADSR envelopes. It expects a gate input or impulses. the second inlet also expects impulses to retrigger. Please read carefully the help files of [envgen~] and [adsr~] as these are very high level and complex objects. By default you have a curvature of "1"., f 63;
#X obj 495 555 adsr~ -minsus 500 -lin 50 150 0.5 250, f 19;
#X obj 468 496 bng 21 250 50 0 empty empty empty 17 7 0 10 #dcdcdc #000000 #000000;
#X text 34 64 The ADSR ("Attack / Decay / Sustain / Release") has a Decay stage after the attack. Here's how it works on [envgen~] with a fixed sustain time (a "one shot" example)., f 48;
#X obj 724 611 *~;
#X obj 665 559 osc~ 440;
#X obj 724 639 out~;
#X obj 742 516 sig~;
#X obj 742 486 tgl 21 0 empty empty empty 0 -10 0 12 #dfdfdf #000000 #000000 0 1;
#X obj 742 547 adsr~ -minsus 500 -maxsus 500 -lin 50 150 0.5 250, f 19;
#X text 425 360 You can also use the 'minsus' message or flag to trigger it with bangs or impulses for a "one shot" example. Below to the left \, it takes 500ms before going into the release stage. We also have a "linear" mode (which is the same as setting the curve factor to 0). You can also combine to the maximum sustain parameter and have it also triggered by a gate. Below to the right it'll go into the release stage after 500ms regardless of the gate off status. Check the help file for more details., f 68;
